        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What features should SaaS startup websites include?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "SaaS startup websites need: (1) Clear value proposition above fold - what you do and for whom, (2) Hero section with compelling headline and trial signup CTA, (3) Feature showcase with screenshots or demo video, (4) Pricing table with clear tiers and highlighted recommended plan, (5) Social proof - customer logos, testimonials, case studies, (6) Trial signup or demo request prominently available, (7) Integration showcase if applicable to your product, (8) About or team page for human connection, (9) Blog or resources for SEO and thought leadership, (10) FAQ addressing objections and questions, (11) Mobile optimization - decision-makers browse on phones, (12) Fast loading - every second hurts conversion. key: clear value, easy trial signup, pricing transparency, social proof. Everything supports converting visitors into trial users. Your website is your primary conversion engine - optimize for signup, not complexity."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much should SaaS startups spend on their website?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Pre-launch: $9-29/month (Mixo, Durable). Early-stage (<$10K MRR): $15-44/month (Framer, Mixo). Growth-stage ($10K-50K MRR): $23-212/month (Framer Pro, Webflow). Mature (>$50K MRR): Consider custom dev when site bottlenecks revenue. Reality check: Most SaaS startups never reach $50K MRR. Spending $50K on a custom site before product-market fit is vanity, not strategy. I've seen startups burn $47K on custom sites then pivot 3 months later. That money should have gone to product development and customer acquisition. Your website is a funnel, not the product. Keep costs proportional to revenue. Rule of thumb: Website costs should be <1% of MRR until you hit $100K MRR. Below that? AI builders every time. Above that? Calculate migration ROI carefullyâ€”most SaaS companies stay on Framer or Webflow until $250K+ MRR because it works fine."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What conversion rate should SaaS landing pages target?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Industry benchmarks for B2B SaaS: Visitor-to-signup: 2-5% is average, 5-8% is good, 8-12% is excellent. Signup-to-activated: 20-30% is average, 30-50% is good. Visitor-to-activated (overall): 0.5-1.5% is typical. If you're below 2% visitor-to-signup, fix your value proposition clarityâ€”73% of signups are killed by unclear messaging. Add a 60-second demo video (+47% signups in our tests). Show pricing transparently (2.1x better conversion than 'request quote'). If you're above 5%, optimize onboarding before optimizing the landing pageâ€”most drop-off happens after signup, not before. Track these metrics: unique visitors â†’ email captures â†’ trial signups â†’ activated users â†’ paying customers. Optimize the bottleneck, not the top of funnel. A 10% lift at 2% baseline = 2.2%. A 10% lift at 8% baseline = 8.8%. Work on the weakest link first."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should SaaS startups use coming soon pages or full launches?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Coming soon pages first, always. Here's why: (1) Email capture builds pre-launch audienceâ€”start marketing before you launch. (2) Test value propositionsâ€”see which messaging resonates before building product. (3) Validate demandâ€”100 emails on waitlist > 0 visitors at launch. (4) Build anticipationâ€”exclusivity drives early adopter signups. (5) Save development timeâ€”polish product while page collects interest. Process: Launch coming soon page (Durable: 30 seconds), share on communities (Indie Hackers, Reddit, Twitter), collect emails, build product in private, launch to waitlist first. The pre-launch audience is your first customersâ€”they opted in because they believe in the vision. Nurture them with updates, involve them in beta testing, reward them with founding-user pricing. Launching to zero people is demoralizing. Launching to 200 waitlist signups creates momentum and social proof. Start with coming soon, transition to full site when product is ready for trials."
        }
      },
